Quayle exhorted, as the crowd erupted in cheers.
Bush, who followed his running mate to the podium, said he was "proud to have Dan Quayle at my side."
Quayle, a hardliner on defense matters, has said he sought guard duty so he could attend law school.
Quayle alluded to the National Guard issue during his speech, saying he was proud of the six years he served.
But Quayle, ever upbeat, was determined Thursday night not to be daunted by the prospect.
"Miracles do happen," he told his party.
